'''Dahr-al-Ain'''   ({{lang-ar| ضهر العين}})  is a village in the [[Koura District]] of [[Lebanon]], with a  [[Maronite Christianity in Lebanon|Maronite]] and  [[Greek Orthodox Christianity in Lebanon|Greek Orthodox]] population.<ref>{{cite web|title=Municipal and ikhtiyariah elections in Northern Lebanon |url=http://www.localiban.org/IMG/pdf/iiMonthly-Municip-Mar10-E92.pdf |publisher=The Monthly |accessdate=29 October 2016 |page=23 |date=March 2010 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160603040803/http://www.localiban.org/IMG/pdf/iiMonthly-Municip-Mar10-E92.pdf |archivedate=3 June 2016 |df= }}</ref>

It attracted media attention in May 2010 when two brothers, Tony and Nayef Saleh, were shot by Hanna al-Bersawi on May 28, apparently for political reasons only days before the municipal polls.<ref>[http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Local-News/May/31/Dahr-al-Ain-murders-raise-tensions-ahead-of-polls.ashx#axzz1PvOAKDM3 Lebanon Daily Star article]</ref>

==History of demographic change==
{{unreferenced section|date=September 2016}}
{{POV section|date=September 2016}}
From recent subdivisions from larger parcels of land that was previously being used for olive harvesting, there have been numerous apartment buildings being built outside of the Dahr Al-Ain main village centre towards the Barsa side of the town (south and south east of the village). The new inhabitants are a mixture of [[Sunni Islam in Lebanon|Sunni Muslims]] (from [[Tripoli, Lebanon|Tripoli]]), [[Eastern Orthodox Christianity in Lebanon|Eastern Orthodox]] and [[Maronite Christianity in Lebanon|Maronites]] from within and the surrounding areas. The buyers and inhabitants of these 5-6 apartment blocks with 4 apartments in each (6 * 4= 24 new families) are mostly from the [[Sunni Islam in Lebanon|Sunni sect of Islam]] who are now unable to afford higher rents and unable to purchase within the tripoli-Al Mina areas. This change in demographics has the ability to shift the demographics of some smaller villagers and towns found closest to the highway south of Tripoli into the Koura. It is estimated that Dahr Al-Ain has a total resident population of 500-700. With the 34 new families, each with the possibility of containing 4 persons per household, that equates to an increase of 96 persons to the village of varying religions as a result from one large piece of land being sold and further subdivided. It would only require a further 4-5 larger pieces of lands to be sold to developers to shift the demographics of the [[Maronite Christianity in Lebanon|Maronite]] majority village to a [[Sunni Islam in Lebanon|Sunni]] majority village. With the increase of Sunni inhabitants into the area (attracted to the cheaper properties and rents or a calculated shift in demographics) services pertaining to the new residents e.g. mosques and schools has the ability to increase sectarian tensions as Dahr Al-Ain does not have a mosque and the closest mosque would be situated 5–10 minutes away in Ras Masqa (above Qalamoun) and one being constructed in Dedde. A similar change in demographics is also occurring but to a higher degree to areas surrounding Qalamoun and Tripoli within Ras Masqa ([[Eastern Orthodox Christianity in Lebanon|Orthodox]] and [[Maronite Christianity in Lebanon|Maronite]] with [[Sunni Islam in Lebanon|Sunni]]), Dedde ([[Eastern Orthodox Christianity in Lebanon|Orthodox]] with [[Sunni Islam in Lebanon|Sunni]]), Barsa ([[Eastern Orthodox Christianity in Lebanon|Orthodox]] and [[Maronite Christianity in Lebanon|Maronite]] with [[Sunni Islam in Lebanon|Sunni]]), Dahr Al-Ain ([[Maronite Christianity in Lebanon|Maronite]] with [[Eastern Orthodox Christianity in Lebanon|Orthodox]] and [[Sunni Islam in Lebanon|Sunni]]), Hret al Khalsa ([[Sunni Islam in Lebanon|Sunni]]) and Semriye ([[Eastern Orthodox Christianity in Lebanon|Orthodox]] with [[Sunni Islam in Lebanon|Sunni]] and [[Maronite Christianity in Lebanon|Maronites]]). These areas are accessible within ease to and from Tripoli (where most people work, study and have family ties) by a newly asphalted highway that travels to the south  from Tripoli through Bahsas and towards Kousba.

