'''Ha''' ({{lang-egy|[[wikt:ḥꜣ#Etymology 3|ḥꜣ]]}}), in [[ancient Egyptian religion]], was a god of the [[Western Desert (Egypt)|Western Desert]] of Egypt. He was associated with the [[Duat]] (the [[underworld]]) and pictured as a man wearing the symbol for desert hills on his head.
Ha was said to protect Egypt from enemies such as invading [[ancient Libya]]ns.<ref>Wilkinson, Richard H. (2003). ''The Complete Gods and Goddesses of Ancient Egypt''. Thames & Hudson. p. 106</ref>
The dinosaur ''[[Hagryphus]]'' ("Ha's griffin") was named after Ha; it was discovered in Utah and Ha's association with the western deserts was carried over to the deserts of the [[Southwestern United States]].<ref>Zanno, L. E. and Sampson, S. D. 2005. A new oviraptorosaur (Theropoda; Maniraptora) from the Late Cretaceous (Campanian) of Utah. Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology 25 (4):897–904, December 2005</ref>
