'''Kaylartha Pagoda''' is a [[Buddhist]] [[Pagoda]] that sits atop the summit of '''Mount Kaylartha''' in [[Mon State]], [[Myanmar]]. Local legend claims that at the foot of Kaylartha Mountain sat the ancient [[Suvarnabhumi|Kingdom of the Gold]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ayudamyanmartravel.com/content/cycling-myanmar-golden-rock-kyaik-hto-area|title= Cycling in Myanmar|accessdate=2017-09-03}}</ref> [[File:Kaylartha Steps.jpg|thumb|A view of the steps that lead up to Kaylartha Pagoda. To the right is the monastic kitchen where nuns cook and serve breakfast and lunch to the monks and visitors.]] {{Infobox mountain | name = Kaylartha | other_name = | photo = | photo_caption=Village home with view of Kaylartha Mountain. | elevation_ft= 1,600 | prominence_m = 2148 | map = Myanmar | map_caption = Location in Burma | map_size = 200 | label_position = bottom | listing = [[List of mountains in Myanmar]] | location = [[Mon State]], [[Burma]] | coordinates = {{coord|17|13|38|N|97|04|51|E|type:mountain_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}} | coordinates_ref = | topo = | first_ascent = Unknown | easiest_route = Drive }}
==Geography==
'''Kaylartha Mountain''' is situated {{convert|3|mi}} from Taungson, [[Mon State]], and can be driven up to by truck. The range is part of the or Eastern [[Arakan Mountains|Arakan Yoma Mountains]]. It is at a distance of {{convert|184|km|mi}} from Yangon and 136 kilometers north of [[Mawlamyine]], the capital of Mon State. The summit is above {{convert|1600|ft}}. Monkeys live atop the mountain and are fed by pilgrims.
==History==
At the top of Mount Kaylartha stands a [[Pagoda|pagoda]] said to house a hair of the [[Gautama Buddha|Buddha]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmtimes.com/special-features/197-travel-2014/11674-once-off-limits-mon-state-reveals-its-beauty.html|title=Myanmar Times, Mon State|accessdate=2017-09-03}}</ref> It is believed that in the Tharthanar Era (111), the [[Gautama Buddha]] arrived at the Kaylartha Mountain, Thuwunna Bonmi. He stayed at a monastery built by [[King Tissa Dama Thiha Yaza]]. The Buddha preached sermons to the public for seven days. During that time, he became close with the [[Hermits Tissa and Thiha]] and the local hermit of Kaylartha Mountain. They requested that he leave behind some relic to be revered by the people in his place after he left to return home. Buddha agreed and gave six of his hairs to hermits from [[Kyaiktiyo Pagoda|Kyaiktiyo]], [[Zinkyaik Pagoda|Zinkyaik]] (to Tissa), [[Mount Zwegabin]] (to Thiha), '''Kaylartha''', [[Kuthaerayone]] and [[Melan]]. A pair of [[Rakshasa|belu]] brothers from [[Kyaikhtisaung Pagoda|Kyaikhtisaung]] also received a hair. All the hermits and belus enshrined the hair in great stones.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmtimes.com/special-features/197-travel-2014/11674-once-off-limits-mon-state-reveals-its-beauty.html|title=Once off-limits, Mon State reveals its beauty|accessdate=2017-09-03}}</ref>{{sfn|Ds. Aung|2015|p=16-17}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sanelettinresort.com/tourist-attraction/kyaik-htee-saung|title=Sane Let Tin|accessdate=2017-09-03}}</ref>{{sfn|U Sann|2013|p=43}}
The Hermit of Kaylartha, whose name was [[Tila of Dokkhalun]],{{sfn|Ds. Aung|2015|p=16}} discussed how to go about enshrining the hairs and building pagodas around them with Hermits Tissa and Thiha and [[Śakra (Buddhism)|Indra Sakka]], who had supported Thiha in constructing a pagoda on Mount [[Zwegabin]]. He enshrined the hair relic in the pagoda atop Kaylartha Mountain, and was advised by Indra Sakka.
The hermits communicated with each other by shining lights atop their respective mountains at nighttime. Tissa, who stayed atop [[Zinkyaik Mountain]], did not see light coming from Mountain Kaylartha and wondered what might have occurred. He went to Kaylartha Mountain and found the body of the Kaylartha Hermit. The body was burnt and buried, while the head, which was not burnt nor decomposed, held one of Buddha's hairs in its braid. It was returned to [[Mok Soe Taung Pagoda]] and joined the original two hair relics there.{{sfn|U Sann|2013|p=45-46}}
==Restoration==
The [[Kyaikhtisaung Sayadaw]] restored nine Buddha hair relic pagodas during his lifetime, with Kaylartha Pagoda being one of them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thegoldenlandofmyanmar.com/bios/bio-kyaithisaung-sayadaw/|title=Bio – Kyaithisaung Sayadaw|accessdate=2017-08-31}}</ref> He built a compound around the pagoda and paved a road up to the top. It is now a popular spot for tourists and locals and had a resident abbot and monastery at the summit of the mountain.
