{{Other uses|Periboea (disambiguation)}}
In [[Greek mythology]], the name '''Periboea''' ({{IPAc-en|ˌ|p|ɛ|r|ᵻ|ˈ|b|iː|ə}}; [[Ancient Greek]]: Περίβοια "surrounded by cattle" derived from ''peri'' "around" and ''boes'' "cattle") refers to multiple figures:
*Periboea, one of the [[Oceanids]]; mother of [[Aura (mythology)|Aura]] by [[Lelantos]].<ref>[[Nonnus]], ''[[Dionysiaca]]'' 48. 264 ff</ref> *Periboea, daughter of the Giant [[Gigantes|Eurymedon]] and the mother of [[Nausithous]] with [[Poseidon]].<ref>[[Homer]], ''[[Odyssey]]'', 7. 56-57</ref> *Periboea, was the daughter of either King [[Cychreus]] of [[Salamis Island|Salamis]] or of Alcathous, her mother in the latter case being either [[Alcathous, son of Pelops|Pyrgo]] or [[Evaechme]], daughter of [[Megareus of Onchestus|Megareus]].<ref>[[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]], ''Description of Greece'', 1. 43. 4</ref> She was ravished by [[Telamon]] who then fled away; when her father learned of that, he ordered for her to be cast in the sea, but the guard who was to perform that took pity on her and sold her away; the one who bought her happened to be Telamon.<ref>[[Pseudo-Plutarch]], ''[[Parallel Lives]]'', 27. 312b</ref> She became by him mother of [[Ajax the Great|Ajax]].<ref>Pseudo-Apollodorus, ''[[Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|Bibliotheca]]'' 3. 12. 7</ref><ref>[[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]], ''Description of Greece'', 1. 42. 1, 1. 17. 3</ref> She was among the would-be [[sacrificial victims of Minotaur]]; while on board the ship, [[Minos]] attempted to sexually abuse her but she was defended by [[Theseus]],<ref>[[Bacchylides]], Ode 17, 8-16</ref> with whom she later consorted.<ref>[[Plutarch]], ''Life of Theseus'', 29. 1</ref><ref>[[Pherecydes of Leros|Pherecydes]] in [[Athenaeus]], 13. 557b. A certain "Phereboea" is also mentioned by him among the wives of Theseus; she could be identical with Periboea</ref> Also known as Eriboea.<ref>[[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]], ''Description of Greece'', 1. 6. 45</ref><ref>[[Sophocles]], ''Ajax'', 566</ref><ref>[[Pindar]], Isthmian Ode 6. 65</ref><ref>[[Hyginus]], ''Fabulae'', 14</ref> *Periboea, wife of [[Polybus of Corinth|Polybus]], foster mother of [[Oedipus]].<ref>''[[Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|Bibliotheca]]'' 3. 5. 7</ref> *Periboea, a [[Naiads|Naiad]], wife of [[Icarius of Sparta|Icarius]], mother of [[Penelope]], [[Perilaus]], Aletes, Damasippus, Imeusimus and Thoas,<ref>''[[Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|Bibliotheca]]'' 3. 10. 6</ref> presumably also of [[Iphthime]].<ref>[[Homer]], ''Odyssey'', 4, 797</ref> Icarius' wife is alternatively known as [[Asterodia]], Dorodoche<ref>[[Scholia]] on [[Homer]], ''Odyssey'', 15. 16</ref> or [[Polycaste]]<ref>[[Strabo]], ''Geography'', 10. 2. 24; her sons by Icarius are called [[Alyzeus]] and [[Leucadius]]</ref> *Periboea, daughter of [[Hipponous]] and mother of [[Tydeus]] by [[Oeneus]].<ref>''[[Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|Bibliotheca]]'' 1. 8. 4</ref><ref>[[Scholia]] on [[Euripides]], ''[[Phoenician Women]]'', 133</ref> *Periboea, one of the first two maidens sent by the people of [[Locris]] to the shrine of [[Athena]] at [[Troy]], in order to relieve them of plague. The other was named [[Cleopatra (Greek myth)|Cleopatra]].<ref>''[[Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|Bibliotheca]]'', Epitome of Book 4, 6. 20-21</ref> *Periboea, eldest daughter of [[Acessamenus]], and mother of [[Pelagon]] by the river-god [[Axius (mythology)|Axius]].<ref>[[Homer]], ''[[Iliad]]'' 20. 142</ref> *Periboea, mother, by [[Meges]], of the [[Troy|Trojans]] [[Celtus]] and [[Eubius]] (Εὔβιος).<ref>[[Quintus Smyrnaeus]], ''Fall of Troy'', 7. 606 ff</ref> *Periboea, a daughter of [[Aeolus#Son of Hippotes|Aeolus]] the wind lord.<ref>[[Scholia]] on ''[[Odyssey]]'', 10. 6</ref>
