The '''Tham Sang Triangle''' refer to a group of four caves in close proximity, located roughly {{convert|8|km}} north of [[Vang Vieng]], [[Laos]], to the northwest of the village of [[Ban Pakpo]]. The four caves are '''Tham Sang''', '''Tham Hoi''', '''Tham Loup''', and '''Tham Nam'''. The name "Tham Sang" refers to the stalactites within them which are said to resemble elephants, a characteristic in particular of the Tham Sang cave.<ref name="GUIDES2011">{{cite book|title=DK Eyewitness Travel Guide: Cambodia & Laos|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xt7kQaNSPMMC&pg=PA234|accessdate=21 July 2012|date=1 June 2011|publisher=Dorling Kindersley Limited|isbn=978-1-4053-4985-7|page=172}}</ref> The entrance has a grey boulder on the right side with a red flower bush beyond that. Tham Hoi is considered the most sacred to locals, with a larger Buddha head in the entrance, whilst Tham Loup is noted for its stalactites.<ref name="GUIDES2011"/> Tham Nam, meaning "water cave", is located roughly {{convert|400|m}} south of Tham Hoi.

